{"slidecode": {"title": "Redland Baptist Church Solar PPA Overview", "subtitle": "Project Summary & Modeling Context", "slidenum": 1, "image_id": "FZiEMuO8EKw", "body": [{"point": "Project Objective", "description": "Implement a solar Power Purchase Agreement (PPA) to reduce electricity costs and environmental impact while preserving upfront capital.", "icon": "fa-solar-panel"}, {"point": "Modeling Assumptions", "description": "PEPCO rate projections (2025–2030), 0.5% annual PV degradation, and zero export value were factored into cost and savings scenarios.", "icon": "fa-calculator"}, {"point": "System Characteristics", "description": "Projected system size of approximately 266 kW producing 301,745 kWh in Year 1 with a performance ratio of 0.87.", "icon": "fa-cogs"}, {"point": "Purpose of Summary", "description": "Present decision-makers with an informed analysis of cost-benefit under varying PPA structures, supporting long-term energy planning.", "icon": "fa-chart-line"}], "talktrack": "The objective of this solar PPA project is both financial and environmental—delivering lower energy costs and a reduced carbon footprint, all without the need for Redland Baptist Church to deploy upfront capital. This slide introduces the scope and methodology of the executive summary.

Key assumptions like the 0.5% annual PV degradation and PEPCO's projected energy rate escalation through 2030 are critical to the modeling framework. These ensure the projections are grounded in regional utility trends.

Ultimately, this summary offers a structured look at economic tradeoffs across different PPA pricing scenarios. It's designed to empower stakeholders with data-backed insights for making confident, strategic energy decisions.", "sources": [], "force_edit": false}}

{"slidecode": {"title": "Key Metrics & Baseline Data", "subtitle": "Foundational Figures for PPA Modeling", "slidenum": 2, "image_id": "JKUTrJ4vK00", "body": [{"point": "Annual Electricity Usage", "description": "Redland's 12-month baseline consumption is 293,975 kWh, setting the reference for energy cost and solar offset analysis.", "icon": "fa-tachometer-alt"}, {"point": "Modeled PV Output", "description": "Projected solar generation is 301,745 kWh in Year 1, exceeding baseline demand, and degrades at 0.5% annually.", "icon": "fa-sun"}, {"point": "Blended Utility Rate", "description": "The baseline utility cost is $0.2031/kWh, compared to a Year-1 PPA rate of $0.1630/kWh under the escalating scenario.", "icon": "fa-dollar-sign"}, {"point": "Year-1 Financial Impact", "description": "Customer cost under the PPA is $56,918 in Year 1, generating $2,817 in savings compared to utility rates.", "icon": "fa-balance-scale"}], "talktrack": "This slide lays out the core performance and financial metrics that form the basis of the solar PPA analysis. The baseline electricity usage of nearly 294,000 kWh per year anchors the assessment of how much solar can offset.

With the system expected to produce over 301,000 kWh in its first year, it not only matches but slightly exceeds annual demand. This positions the project for significant offset, even as the system degrades modestly over time.

By locking into a lower initial PPA rate of $0.1630/kWh, the Church achieves immediate savings—over $2,800 in Year 1 alone—against utility rates forecasted to increase. These metrics demonstrate that even in the early phase, the economic case for solar is compelling.", "sources": [], "force_edit": false}}

{"slidecode": {"title": "PEPCO Projections vs. PPA Rates", "subtitle": "Cost Trends from 2025 to 2030", "slidenum": 3, "image_id": "-iaHr12PVQg", "body": [{"point": "PEPCO Rate Escalation", "description": "PEPCO's projected rates increase from $0.2100 in 2025 to $0.2928/kWh by 2030, representing a 39% cumulative rise.", "icon": "fa-chart-line"}, {"point": "PPA Cost Stability", "description": "The PPA begins at $0.1630/kWh with a 2% annual escalator, reaching only $0.1800/kWh by 2030—a much flatter curve.", "icon": "fa-compress-arrows-alt"}, {"point": "Year-by-Year Savings", "description": "Savings grow from $0.0470/kWh in 2025 to $0.1128/kWh in 2030, translating to 22.4%–38.5% cost reduction annually.", "icon": "fa-percentage"}, {"point": "Economic Hedge Against Inflation", "description": "The PPA structure offers predictable pricing, insulating the Church from volatile and rising utility rates.", "icon": "fa-shield-alt"}], "talktrack": "This comparison highlights the fundamental economic advantage of a solar PPA versus remaining on utility power alone. PEPCO's rates are projected to increase sharply over the next five years—from $0.2100 to nearly $0.2930/kWh. In contrast, the PPA rate only grows modestly, preserving long-term affordability.

The year-by-year analysis underscores how savings accelerate over time. While initial savings are already respectable at 22%, they expand beyond 38% by 2030. This trendline strengthens the case for early adoption.

Perhaps most importantly, the PPA acts as a hedge—offering cost certainty and financial control in an environment where energy pricing can be unpredictable and inflationary.", "sources": [], "force_edit": false}}

{"slidecode":{"title":"PEPCO Projections vs. PPA Rates","subtitle":"2025–2030 Comparative Electricity Pricing","slidenum":4,"image_id":"","body":[{"point":"PEPCO Rate Forecast","description":"Energy-only rates expected to rise from $0.2100/kWh in 2025 to $0.2928/kWh by 2030, based on utility projections.","icon":"fa-chart-line"},{"point":"PPA Rate Trajectory","description":"PPA starts at $0.1630/kWh in 2025 with a 2% annual increase, reaching $0.1800/kWh by 2030—well below PEPCO rates.","icon":"fa-long-arrow-alt-up"},{"point":"Cost Delta & Savings","description":"Annual savings rise from $0.0470/kWh (22.4%) in 2025 to $0.1128/kWh (38.5%) in 2030 under the PPA structure.","icon":"fa-percentage"},{"point":"Strategic Implication","description":"PPA structure offers long-term protection from utility inflation, enabling consistent budgeting and energy cost control.","icon":"fa-shield-alt"}],"talktrack":"This slide presents a clear side-by-side comparison of the expected evolution of electricity rates under PEPCO and the proposed PPA. The PEPCO forecast shows a steady increase in utility rates—climbing nearly 40% from 2025 to 2030. These projections form the baseline against which the PPA's value is evaluated.

The PPA, in contrast, begins at a significantly lower rate and increases only marginally over the same period. Even with its 2% escalator, the PPA remains far more affordable, reaching just $0.1800 by 2030.

This widening gap in price trajectories translates into increasing savings for Redland Baptist Church year after year. More importantly, the fixed nature of the PPA introduces financial stability—a strategic hedge against future energy inflation.","sources":[],"force_edit":false}}

{"slidecode": {"title": "Scenario A: PPA with 2% Escalator", "subtitle": "Annual Costs and Savings (2026–2030)", "slidenum": 5, "image_id": "Wp7wotWlbBk", "body": [{"point": "PPA Payment Growth", "description": "Annual PPA payments grow from $49,917 in 2026 to $52,960 in 2030, tracking the 2% escalation schedule.", "icon": "fa-chart-line"}, {"point": "Imports Cost", "description": "Supplemental utility imports range from $9,901 to $11,146 annually, ensuring full energy coverage.", "icon": "fa-plug"}, {"point": "Total Cost Under PPA", "description": "Total annual costs (PPA + imports) rise from $59,818 in 2026 to $64,106 by 2030, still well below utility baseline.", "icon": "fa-dollar-sign"}, {"point": "Annual Savings vs. Utility", "description": "Savings improve yearly—from $16,616 in 2026 to $21,970 in 2030—totaling over $96,000 across five years.", "icon": "fa-piggy-bank"}], "talktrack": "This scenario models a PPA starting at $0.1630/kWh with a 2% annual escalator, reflecting a common contract structure for long-term solar agreements. Even with modest rate growth, the PPA remains financially advantageous.

The Church's payments rise gradually from just under $50,000 in 2026 to roughly $53,000 by 2030. When utility imports are included, total costs range from $59,818 to $64,106 annually—consistently lower than projected utility bills.

Crucially, the savings compound each year as PEPCO rates increase. Cumulatively, this adds up to more than $96,000 in avoided costs over five years, supporting both fiscal stewardship and long-term sustainability.", "sources": [], "force_edit": false}}
